<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="127" type="morphological variation">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Morphological variation.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
The paratype is a colony consisting of ~10 polyps. Polyps of the paratype colony show variation in colouration; the whitish colour is not restricted to the oral disk but is also seen in the tentacles. This could be due to differences in sclerite density (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Bunga payung gen. nov. et sp. nov.: a In situ photograph, holotype (NSMT-Co 1679) b In situ photograph, paratype (IPMB-C 01.00017) c holotype in ethanol. Laeta waheedae gen. nov. et sp. nov. d holotype (NSMT-Co 1680) in ethanol e In situ photograph, holotype f In situ photograph, paratype (IPMB-C 01.00019). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.872.36288.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/328189" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Figure 2a</figureCitation>
), as described in 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.1400.1.2" author="Alderslade, P" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" pagination="27 - 44" refId="B5" refString="Alderslade, P, McFadden, CS, 2007. Pinnule-less polyps: a new genus and new species of Indo-Pacific Clavulariidae and validation of the soft coral genus Acrossota and the family Acrossotidae (Coelenterata: Octocorallia). . Zootaxa 1400: 27 - 44" title="Pinnule-less polyps: a new genus and new species of Indo-Pacific Clavulariidae and validation of the soft coral genus Acrossota and the family Acrossotidae (Coelenterata: Octocorallia)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.1400.1.2" volume="1400" year="2007">Alderslade and McFadden (2007)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/18759866-20191355" author="Lau, YW" journalOrPublisher="Contributions to Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" pagination="54 - 77" refId="B41" refString="Lau, YW, Stokvis, FR, Imahara, Y, Reimer, JD, 2019. The stoloniferous octocoral, Hanabirayukibana, gen. nov., sp. nov., of the southern Ryukyus has morphological and symbiont variation. . Contributions to Zoology 88: 54 - 77" title="The stoloniferous octocoral, Hanabirayukibana, gen. nov., sp. nov., of the southern Ryukyus has morphological and symbiont variation." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/18759866-20191355" volume="88" year="2019">Lau et al. (2019)</bibRefCitation>
, or it could be due to the position of zooxanthellae in the tissue.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
